## 🚫 Common Refactoring Pitfalls

### Pitfall 1: Changing Behavior While Refactoring

```go
// ❌ BAD: Adding new validation
func (s *AccountService) Deposit(amount decimal.Decimal) error {
    if amount.LessThan(decimal.NewFromInt(10)) {
        return ErrMinimumDeposit  // NEW logic!
    }
    // ...
}

// ✅ GOOD: Keeping exact same logic
func (s *AccountService) Deposit(amount decimal.Decimal) error {
    // Same validation as before refactoring
    if amount.LessThanOrEqual(decimal.Zero) {
        return ErrInvalidAmount
    }
    // ...
}
```

### Pitfall 2: Over-Engineering Interfaces

```go
// ❌ BAD: Interface with unused methods
type WalletService interface {
    Credit(...)
    Debit(...)
    Transfer(...)       // Not used in Phase 0/1!
    GetHistory(...)     // Not used in Phase 0/1!
    CreateWallet(...)   // Not used in Phase 0/1!
    UpdateMetadata(...) // Not used in Phase 0/1!
    FreezeWallet(...)   // Not used in Phase 0/1!
}

// ✅ GOOD: Minimal interface (only what's used)
type WalletService interface {
    Credit(ctx context.Context, req CreditRequest) (*WalletTransaction, error)
    Debit(ctx context.Context, req DebitRequest) (*WalletTransaction, error)
    GetBalance(ctx context.Context, walletID string) (*Balance, error)
}
```

### Pitfall 3: Leaking Vendor Types

```go
// ❌ BAD: Vendor types in interface
import formance "github.com/formancehq/formance-sdk-go"

type WalletService interface {
    Credit(ctx context.Context, req *formance.CreditRequest) (*formance.CreditResponse, error)
}

// ✅ GOOD: Domain types only
type WalletService interface {
    Credit(ctx context.Context, req CreditRequest) (*WalletTransaction, error)
}

type CreditRequest struct {
    WalletID  string
    Amount    Money  // Domain type
    Reference string
    Metadata  map[string]string
}
```

### Pitfall 4: Not Creating In-Memory Adapters

```go
// ❌ BAD: Only creating production adapter
// infrastructure/adapters/wallet/
//   formance_wallet_adapter.go  (only this!)

// ✅ GOOD: Creating both production and in-memory
// infrastructure/adapters/wallet/
//   formance_wallet_adapter.go
//   inmemory_wallet_adapter.go
//   tigerbeetle_wallet_adapter.go (optional alternative)
```

### Pitfall 5: Breaking Tests During Refactoring

```go
// ❌ BAD: Refactoring code without updating tests
// (tests will fail)

// ✅ GOOD: Update tests immediately after refactoring
func TestAccountService_Deposit(t *testing.T) {
    // Use in-memory adapters
    walletAdapter := wallet.NewInMemoryWalletAdapter()
    service := NewAccountService(walletAdapter, ...)

    // Test should pass
}
```

